04028nam a22005055i 9780228002307DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280023077 a10.1515/97802280023072doi  a(DE-B1597)655124  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aP95.82.S97 7aPOL0590002bisacsh04a302.230956912231 aBrownlee, Billie Jeanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Media and Revolution :bResistance and Dissent in Pre-uprising Syria /cBillie Jeanne Brownlee. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b9 photos, 8 diagrams, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Protest, Power, and Resistance ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tNew Media, New Battlefields for New Revolutions -- tFrom Virtual to Tangible Civic Mobilisation -- t‘Change within Continuity’: The Lion Cub’s Reforms -- tEmpowering Publics: Satellite TV and the Internet -- tMedia Development and Foreign Aid Assistance -- tThe Syrian Media Landscape after 2011 -- tConclusions – Media: Weapons of the Weak or the Weapons of Mass Distraction? -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Arab Spring did not arise out of nowhere. It was the physical manifestation of more than a decade of new media diffusion, use, and experimentation that empowered ordinary people during their everyday lives. In this book, Billie Jeanne Brownlee offers a refreshing insight into the way new media can facilitate a culture of resistance and dissent in authoritarian states.Investigating the root causes of the Syrian uprising of 2011, New Media and Revolution shows how acts of online resistance prepared the ground for better-organised street mobilisation. The book interprets the uprising not as the start of Syria's social mobilisation but as a shift from online to offline contestation, and from localised and hidden practices of digital dissent to tangible mass street protests. Brownlee goes beyond the common dichotomy that frames new media as either a deus ex machina or a means of expression to demonstrate that, in Syria, media was a nontraditional institution that enabled resistance to digitally manifest and gestate below, within, and parallel to formal institutions of power. To refute the idea that the population of Syria was largely apathetic and apolitical prior to the uprising, Brownlee explains that social media and technology created camouflaged geographies and spaces where individuals could protest without being detected.Challenging the myth of authoritarian stability, New Media and Revolution uncovers the dynamics of grassroots resistance blossoming under the radar of ordinary politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszSyria. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszSyria. 0aSocial changezSyria. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800230740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002307423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002307/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles